{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a72cd9180d89b1f4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2603.14877 ===\n# SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Play Streaming State Prediction Module for Realtime Full-Duplex Speech Conversation\narXiv: 2603.14877\nAuthors: Ruiqi Yan, Wenxi Chen, Zhanxun Liu, Ziyang Ma, Haopeng Lin, Hanlin Wen, Hanke Xie, Jun Wu, Yuzhe Liang, Yuxiang Zhao, Pengchao Feng, Jiale Qian, Hao Meng, Yuhang Dai, Shunshun Yin, Ming Tao, Lei Xie, Kai Yu, Xinsheng Wang, Xie Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoulX-Duplug, a bilingual streaming state prediction module that unifies VAD, ASR, and turn detection within a single framework to enable low-latency and semantically informed dialogue state control for modular full-duplex spoken dialogue systems.\n  2. We release SoulX-Duplug-Eval, a complementary benchmark that extends the Easy Turn testset and Full-Duplex-Bench, promoting more standardized and comparable cross-lingual assessment in future research.\n  3. SoulX-Duplug achieves streaming turn detection with an average latency of 240\\,ms, and a full-duplex spoken dialogue system built upon it outperforms existing systems across multiple evaluation settings, validating its downstream practicality.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, ASR, ASR/隐式对齐-AED\n=== 2604.12928 ===\n# MoshiRAG: Asynchronous Knowledge Retrieval for Full-Duplex Speech Language Models\narXiv: 2604.12928\nAuthors: Chung-Ming Chien, Manu Orsini, Eugene Kharitonov, Neil Zeghidour, Karen Livescu, Alexandre Défossez\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_agent\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes MoshiRAG, the first full-duplex speech language model equipped with retrieval-augmented generation to improve factuality without sacrificing real-time interactivity.\n  2. Introduces an asynchronous framework that exploits the natural temporal gap between response onset and core information delivery to seamlessly integrate external knowledge during conversation.\n  3. Develops a specialized training methodology with synthetic data that teaches the model to predict a retrieval trigger token and generate conversational filler while the back end fetches information.\n  4. Demonstrates that MoshiRAG achieves factuality comparable to the best turn-based speech language models while maintaining the low latency and full-duplex interactivity of the base Moshi model.\n  5. Shows that the modular design enables plug-and-play replacement of retrieval back ends at inference time, allowing performance improvements without retraining.\n  6. Validates strong out-of-domain generalization by successfully applying the retrieval mechanism as a tool to solve unseen mathematical reasoning tasks.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, Agent, Agent/Action\n=== 2410.00037 ===\n# Moshi: a speech-text foundation model for real-time dialogue\narXiv: 2410.00037\nAuthors: Alexandre Défossez, Laurent Mazaré, Manu Orsini, Amélie Royer, Patrick Pérez, Hervé Jégou, Edouard Grave, Neil Zeghidour\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present Helium, a 7B-parameter text LLM pre-trained on 2.1T tokens of filtered public English data.\n  2. We train Mimi, a neural audio codec that distills semantic information into the first level of acoustic tokens using a split residual vector quantizer.\n  3. We propose a new hierarchical, streaming architecture for audio language modeling that extends the RQ-Transformer with per-codebook parameters and acoustic delays to jointly generate semantic and acoustic tokens.\n  4. We introduce a multi-stream audio language model architecture that explicitly processes the input and output audio streams in parallel to handle full-duplex dialogues with arbitrary conversational dynamics.\n  5. We introduce Inner Monologue, a training and inference method that predicts time-aligned text tokens as a prefix to audio tokens to significantly improve the linguistic quality of generated speech while remaining compatible with streaming inference.\n  6. We demonstrate that adjusting the delay between text and audio tokens within the Inner Monologue framework allows a single model to function as both a streaming ASR and a streaming TTS system.\n\nTags: LALM, 压缩, TTS, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-混合, TTS/功能-流式\n=== 2508.07375 ===\n# TurnGuide: Enhancing Meaningful Full Duplex Spoken Interactions via Dynamic Turn-Level Text-Speech Interleaving\narXiv: 2508.07375\nAuthors: Wenqian Cui, Lei Zhu, Xiaohui Li, Zhihan Guo, Haoli Bai, Lu Hou, Irwin King\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose TurnGuide, a novel text-speech interleaved generation approach for end-to-end full-duplex speech language models grounded in natural speech data.\n  2. We introduce a dynamic turn segmentation framework to address the insertion timing and length challenges of integrating text into double-channel dialogues.\n  3. We introduce a text-guided dialogue modeling framework that interleaves text and speech generation at the turn level to preserve natural acoustic flow.\n  4. We demonstrate through extensive experiments that TurnGuide significantly improves the semantic coherence of generated speech and achieves state-of-the-art performance on turn-taking events.\n\nTags: LALM/对话型-交错标记, LALM/对话型-纯语音, Agent/全双工\n=== 2603.13686 ===\n# $τ$-Voice: Benchmarking Full-Duplex Voice Agents on Real-World Domains\narXiv: 2603.13686\nAuthors: Soham Ray, Keshav Dhandhania, Victor Barres, Karthik Narasimhan\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_agent\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A voice agent benchmark combining verifiable completion of complex grounded tasks, full-duplex interaction, and realistic audio.\n  2. A controllable and realistic voice user simulator with diverse accents, realistic audio environments, and rich turn-taking dynamics.\n  3. Empirical findings revealing a substantial voice-text gap where voice agents retain only 30-45% of text capability under realistic conditions.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/基准, Eval/情感语境交互, Eval/安全性, Agent, Agent/对话型LALM\n=== 2504.08528 ===\n# On The Landscape of Spoken Language Models: A Comprehensive Survey\narXiv: 2504.08528\nAuthors: Siddhant Arora, Kai-Wei Chang, Chung-Ming Chien, Yifan Peng, Haibin Wu, Yossi Adi, Emmanuel Dupoux, Hung-Yi Lee, Karen Livescu, Shinji Watanabe\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Provided a unified formulation and terminology for spoken language models (SLMs) by categorizing them into pure speech LMs, speech+text LMs, and speech-aware text LMs.\n  2. Categorized existing SLM research by detailing key design choices for model architecture, including speech encoders, modality adapters, sequence models, and speech decoders.\n  3. Outlined training strategies for SLMs by distinguishing between pre-training techniques and post-training methods like instruction tuning and preference optimization.\n  4. Reviewed architectural approaches for full-duplex spoken dialogue, specifically contrasting dual-channel and time-multiplexing strategies for handling simultaneous listening and speaking.\n  5. Organized existing evaluation methods and benchmarks for SLMs across likelihood-based metrics, generative metrics, interactivity measures, and trustworthiness assessments.\n  6. Identified key open challenges and future research directions, highlighting limitations in model architecture, training data, standardized evaluation, open-source availability, and safety.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型, LALM/音频标记-融合, LALM/潜在表示\n=== 2411.13577 ===\n# WavChat: A Survey of Spoken Dialogue Models\narXiv: 2411.13577\nAuthors: Shengpeng Ji, Yifu Chen, Minghui Fang, Jialong Zuo, Jingyu Lu, Hanting Wang, Ziyue Jiang, Long Zhou, Shujie Liu, Xize Cheng, Xiaoda Yang, Zehan Wang, Qian Yang, Jian Li, Yidi Jiang, Jingzhen He, Yunfei Chu, Jin Xu, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2024 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Categorization of existing spoken dialogue systems into cascaded and end-to-end paradigms based on whether the core language model directly understands and generates speech representations.\n  2. In-depth overview of core technologies including speech representation, training paradigms, streaming capabilities, and duplex interaction mechanisms.\n  3. Discussion of the limitations of current speech representations and training paradigms, outlining considerations for future research in these areas.\n  4. Thorough review of relevant training datasets, evaluation metrics, and benchmarks from the perspectives of training and evaluating spoken dialogue systems.\n\nTags: LALM, LALM/对话型", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "05a84137-1043-4d6d-8eea-0a344efe0fbd", "uuid": "c84c8017-e72d-43c9-ac89-30a454ad8af3", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T11:17:19.696Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2603.14877 ===\n# SoulX-Duplug: Plug-and-Play Streaming State Prediction Module for Realtime Full-Duplex Speech Conversation\narXiv: 2603.14877\nAuthors: Ruiqi Yan, Wenxi Chen, Zhanxun Liu, Ziyang Ma, Haopeng Lin, Hanlin Wen, Hanke Xie, Jun Wu, Yuzhe Liang, Yuxiang Zhao, Pengchao Feng, Jiale Qian, Hao Meng, Yuhang Dai, Shunshun Yin, Ming Tao, Lei Xie, Kai Yu, Xinsheng Wang, Xie Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose SoulX-Duplug, a bilingual streaming state prediction module that unifies VAD, ASR, and turn detection within a single framework to enable low-latency and semantically informed dialogue state control for modular full-duplex spoken dialogue systems.\n  2. We release SoulX-Duplug-Eval, a complementary benchmark that extends the Easy Turn testset and Full-Duplex-Bench, promoting more standardized and comparable cross-lingual assessment in future research.\n  3. SoulX-Duplug achieves streaming turn detection with an average latency of 240\\,