{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a2816011749afe0f", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2502.17810 ===\n# URO-Bench: Towards Comprehensive Evaluation for End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Models\narXiv: 2502.17810\nAuthors: Ruiqi Yan, Xiquan Li, Wenxi Chen, Zhikang Niu, Chen Yang, Ziyang Ma, Kai Yu, Xie Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of URO-Bench, the first comprehensive speech-to-speech benchmark for end-to-end spoken dialogue models covering multilingualism, multi-round dialogues, and paralinguistics.\n  2. Design of a two-track evaluation framework (basic and pro) comprising 20 tasks to assess spoken dialogue models across the dimensions of understanding, reasoning, and oral conversation.\n  3. Development of a systematic benchmark construction pipeline that integrates existing textual datasets, LLM-generated data, and state-of-the-art TTS synthesis with rigorous quality control.\n  4. Inclusion of novel evaluation metrics for speech-to-speech scenarios, specifically UTMOS for speech quality, ASR-WER/CER for speech-text alignment, and first packet latency for response speed.\n=== 2602.12135 ===\n# WavBench: Benchmarking Reasoning, Colloquialism, and Paralinguistics for End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Models\narXiv: 2602.12135\nAuthors: Yangzhuo Li, Shengpeng Ji, Yifu Chen, Tianle Liang, Haorong Ying, Yule Wang, Junbo Li, Jun Fang, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_dataset\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We propose WavBench, a comprehensive benchmark tailored for authentic real-world scenarios that evaluates both audio-centric colloquial semantics and paralinguistic fidelity of end-to-end spoken dialogue models through a three-tiered framework (Pro, Basic, and Acoustic).\n  2. WavBench introduces a hierarchical structure covering seven cognitive domains (Math, Logic, Code, Creative Writing, Safety, Instruction Following, and Common QA) to evaluate spoken adaptation capabilities across both high-difficulty reasoning (Pro) and routine interactions (Basic).\n  3. WavBench assesses comprehensive paralinguistic interactions across 10 dimensions, including speaker information, acoustic characteristics, and background sounds, via both explicit instruction understanding/generation and implicit dialogue scenarios.\n  4. We conducted a comprehensive evaluation of five state-of-the-art end-to-end spoken dialogue models, offering critical insights into the intersection of complex reasoning, colloquial delivery, and paralinguistic fidelity.\n=== 2601.11141 ===\n# FlashLabs Chroma 1.0: A Real-Time End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Model with Personalized Voice Cloning\narXiv: 2601.11141\nAuthors: Tanyu Chen, Tairan Chen, Kai Shen, Zhenghua Bao, Zhihui Zhang, Man Yuan, Yi Shi\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: tts_vc\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. A streaming architecture that tightly couples speech understanding with speech generation through semantic state representations, enabling sub-second end-to-end latency.\n  2. High-fidelity voice cloning that conditions the generation model on audio embeddings from just a few seconds of reference audio, achieving 10.96% relative improvement in speaker similarity over human baseline.\n  3. An interleaved text-audio token schedule (1:2) that enables synchronized generation of acoustic codes with incremental text output, achieving real-time streaming synthesis.\n  4. Strong reasoning and dialogue capabilities with only 4B parameters, demonstrating competitive performance across understanding, reasoning, and oral conversation tasks.\n=== 2604.14932 ===\n# WavAlign: Enhancing Intelligence and Expressiveness in Spoken Dialogue Models via Adaptive Hybrid Post-Training\narXiv: 2604.14932\nAuthors: Yifu Chen, Shengpeng Ji, Qian Chen, Tianle Liang, Yangzhuo Li, Ziqing Wang, Wen Wang, Jingyu Lu, Haoxiao Wang, Xueyi Pu, Fan Zhuo, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: dialogue_system\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We identify and characterize key failure modes of unified sequence-level preference optimization for mixed text--speech outputs, including weak cross-modal coupling, gradient-energy imbalance, and noisy acoustic rewards.\n  2. We propose a single-stage adaptive hybrid post-training scheme that applies preference optimization to text tokens while anchoring speech tokens with SFT, coupled with a rollout-reliability gating mechanism for stable updates.\n  3. Experiments across architectures and benchmarks show consistent gains in both semantic quality and acoustic expressiveness.\n\n=== 2604.15710 ===\n# VoxMind: An End-to-End Agentic Spoken Dialogue System\narXiv: 2604.15710\nAuthors: Tianle Liang, Yifu Chen, Shengpeng Ji, Yijun Chen, Zhiyang Jia, Jingyu Lu, Fan Zhuo, Xueyi Pu, Yangzhuo Li, Zhou Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_agent\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We formulate a formal definition for End-to-End Spoken Agents and propose VoxMind, a unified model that incorporates a \"Think-before-Speak\" paradigm to execute complex reasoning and tool-use tasks.\n  2. We construct AgentChat, a speech dataset annotated with reasoning trajectories, tool interactions, and complex planning paths to alleviate the scarcity of agentic supervision in spoken contexts.\n  3. We design a Multi-Agent Dynamic Tool Management architecture that employs an asynchronous parallel execution strategy to decouple inference latency from the size of the tool library.", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "05a84137-1043-4d6d-8eea-0a344efe0fbd", "uuid": "98f5c518-2d9b-4eba-91ae-69a62e9f345f", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T11:17:36.205Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2502.17810 ===\n# URO-Bench: Towards Comprehensive Evaluation for End-to-End Spoken Dialogue Models\narXiv: 2502.17810\nAuthors: Ruiqi Yan, Xiquan Li, Wenxi Chen, Zhikang Niu, Chen Yang, Ziyang Ma, Kai Yu, Xie Chen\nYear: 2025 | Venue: 